    <string name="metric_about_fmt">About %s</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_steps">Steps count movement detected by the watch accelerometer throughout the day. Walking at least 8,000–10,000 steps daily helps maintain a healthy heart and manage weight.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_calories">Estimated active energy expenditure calculated from your steps, heart rate and profile data. It is an approximation, useful for comparing your activity day to day.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_distance">Estimated distance traveled based on step count and average stride length. Walk or run with the watch on to accumulate distance.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_blood_oxygen">Blood oxygen saturation (SpO₂) shows the percentage of oxygen carried by your red blood cells. A normal resting value is between 95% and 100%. Persistently low values should be discussed with a healthcare professional.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_stress">Stress level is estimated from your heart rate variability (HRV). High values suggest tension; deep breathing and rest usually help lower it.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_blood_pressure">Blood pressure is shown as systolic/diastolic (mmHg). A reference value is around 120/80. Watch measurements are indicative and do not replace a clinical sphygmomanometer.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_sleep">Sleep is divided into stages: deep sleep (restorative), light sleep, REM and awake periods. The ideal for adults is 7–9 hours with sufficient deep and REM sleep. Maintaining a regular sleep schedule improves quality.</string>
    <string name="metric_desc_heart_rate">Heart rate is beats per minute (BPM). At rest, an adult is typically between 60 and 100 BPM. It rises with exercise and drops during rest; observing its trend helps understand your fitness level.</string>

